04333nam a22006495i 9780292737402DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212012txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011020856  a97802927374027 a10.7560/7287072doi  a(DE-B1597)586990  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aPN1998.3.S3948bE85 2012 7aBIO0000002bisacsh04a791.430232091 aErish, Andrew A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCol. William N. Selig, the Man Who Invented Hollywood /cAndrew A. Erish. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (315 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: The Forgotten Pioneer -- t1. The Birth of a Motion Picture Company -- t2. Making Westerns in the West -- t3. The Creation of the Movie Cowboy -- t4. Selig in Eden: The Genesis of Movies in Los Angeles -- t5. Selig’s Cinematic Jungles and Zoo -- t6. Leading the World -- t7. Actualities, Expeditions, and Newsreels -- t8. The Development of the Feature Film -- t9. Exiled from Eden -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSuggested Reading and Selected Selig Filmography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAll histories of Hollywood are wrong. Why? Two words: Colonel Selig. This early pioneer laid the foundation for the movie industry that we know today. Active from 1896 to 1938, William N. Selig was responsible for an amazing series of firsts, including the first two-reel narrative film and the first two-hour narrative feature made in America; the first American movie serial with cliffhanger endings; the first westerns filmed in the West with real cowboys and Indians; the creation of the jungle-adventure genre; the first horror film in America; the first successful American newsreel (made in partnership with William Randolph Hearst); and the first permanent film studio in Los Angeles. Selig was also among the first to cultivate extensive international exhibition of American films, which created a worldwide audience and contributed to American domination of the medium. In this book, Andrew Erish delves into the virtually untouched Selig archive at the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences Library to tell the fascinating story of this unjustly forgotten film pioneer. He traces Selig’s career from his early work as a traveling magician in the Midwest, to his founding of the first movie studio in Los Angeles in 1909, to his landmark series of innovations that still influence the film industry. As Erish recounts the many accomplishments of the man who first recognized that Southern California is the perfect place for moviemaking, he convincingly demonstrates that while others have been credited with inventing Hollywood, Colonel Selig is actually the one who most deserves that honor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMotion picture producers and directorszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72870740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292737402423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292737402/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK